          <text>
                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p>
                                        <add>
                                                  <hi rend="underline">Hebrew</hi>
                                        </add>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)"
                                                  ><placeName>Pittsburgh</placeName>—<date>1853</date></p>
                              <p rend="indent(3)">(evidently during <date>Succoth</date>)</p>
                              <p>To my dear friend, rabbi, sage, honored,<lb/> famous etc. etc.</p>
                              <p>My friend,</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">In going to <placeName>Cleveland</placeName> I
                                        stopped here<lb/> until after <date>Yom Kippur</date>, and
                                        found here a<lb/> fine and worthy congregation, with men
                                        of<lb/> parts and learning, good and true. I also<lb/> found
                                        here one of the sons of <persName>Mr.
                                        Yaroslavsky</persName><lb/> with whom I used to be
                                        acquainted in <placeName>Charleston</placeName><lb/> In the
                                        evening we discussed their congregational<lb/> matters, and
                                        the conversation turned upon me.<lb/> In sum, they consented
                                        that I stay with<lb/> them. I <del>have found</del> find
                                        myself, therefore,<lb/> obliged to let you know at once.
                                        To<lb/> myself I apply the Biblical verse, “God<lb/> will
                                        hear when I call upon Him,” for God<lb/> has helped me. The
                                        people of <placeName>Montgomery</placeName><lb/> had said
                                        that they would do everything<lb/> in their power to prevent
                                        me from obtain-<lb/>ing a position anywhere in
                                                  <placeName>America</placeName>,<lb/> and I apply
                                        to myself “Thus do I know</p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p>that you delight in me, that mine enemy<lb/> will not shout over
                                        me”* I am sure<lb/> that you will stand by my just cause
                                        and<lb/> will support me and give me aid, and renew<lb/> my
                                        station as of old. This I must ask you<lb/>
                                        <del>that if</del> in case any thing new takes place
                                        with<lb/> regard to the well-known affair <add>?</add><lb/>
                                        Also please, for God's sake, send me the<lb/> address of
                                                  <persName>Mr. Yaroslavsky</persName>, and I shall
                                        return<lb/> it.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I am certain, that, with God's help, I<lb/> shall
                                        find rest here, and will be able to<lb/> study English. By
                                        the hand of a traveler<lb/> in the near future I shall send
                                        what I owe<lb/> for the Occident which you will please
                                        send<lb/> to the above address. You, my friend are<lb/> ? an
                                        unusual man and I am unable to<lb/> write a letter fit for a
                                        man like you. Therefore<lb/> I ask your pardon for this
                                        letter. I am<lb/> sure you will not give credence to
                                        slanderers,<lb/> and will not be <del>from</del> among the
                                        purveyors of<lb/> slander.</p>
                              <p>*Ps. 41:12</p>
                              <pb n="3"/>
                              <p>May God extend your years in joy. That is<lb/> my wish and that of
                                        all friends.</p>
                              <p rend="“these rhyme” written in left margin next to following lines"
                                        >Looking for your reply<lb/>Trusting in your aid,<lb/>and in
                                        the aid of Him Who guards this congregation<lb/>the
                                        Congregation of <placeName>Jeshurun</placeName> His chosen
                                        one<lb/>and who calls it His only one,<lb/>just as He is one
                                        and only.<lb/>And the righteous shall live by his faith.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">
                                        <persName role="author">Menachem Elya Marcussohn</persName>
                              </p>
